%I A393664 #9 Mar 04 2026 14:58:06
%S A393664 175,344,648,931,1284,1708,2228,3005,3960,5348,6982,9301,12297,16649,
%T A393664 22316,29610
%N A393664 Maximum side length of a compound perfect squared square (CPSS) of order n.
%C A393664 A squared square is "compound" if it contains at least one smaller squared rectangle, and "perfect" if all of its component squares have distinct sizes. The lowest possible order for a CPSS is 24 (discovered by T. H. Willcocks in 1948).
%C A393664 The maximum side lengths for orders n=24 through n=32 were generated by S. Anderson and L. Milla by mapping planar map classes of 2-connected, minimum degree 3 planar graph embeddings to electrical resistor networks (a method similar to that used by I. Gambini in 1999).
%C A393664 The base graphs were enumerated and generated using B. D. McKay and G. Brinkmann's plantri software (using switches such as plantri -pc2m3xv). To filter out graphs that natively produce imperfect solutions, degree 2 vertices were strictly prohibited (homeomorphically irreducible), as they force adjacent identical currents. Furthermore, 2-connected map generation yields unequal graph/dual counts due to multi-edge duals. These multi-edge configurations were systematically excluded during CPSS processing as they inherently produce squares of identical sizes (unless the battery edge aligns with a multi-edge, which yields a trivial Compound Perfect Squared Rectangle, but not a CPSS).
%C A393664 The bounds for n=33 to n=39 were heavily extended by Jim Williams. Williams bypassed plantri by writing custom, isomorph-free generation software to prune some of the combinatorial explosion, pairing it with a Cholesky decomposition matrix solver. He computationally matched perfect rectangles and almost perfect squares of identical aspect ratios to assemble the massive higher-order compound dissections.
%C A393664 Empirical observation: The maximum side length of CPSS scales asymptotically by a factor of approximately 1.37 per order n. This closely matches the 1.36 growth factor observed in Simple Perfect Squared Squares (SPSS, see A217149), meaning constrained squares grow at roughly the square root of the rate of unconstrained simple squared rectangles (which scale by  approximately 1.77 per order).
%C A393664 Empirical observation: Logarithmic regression of the data up to n = 39 indicates an asymptotic growth scaling factor of approximately 1.37 per order. A curve fit suggests a(n) approximately equal to exp(0.3146*n - 1.8523). A formal proof of this asymptotic growth rate is not yet known.
%D A393664 R. L. Brooks, C. A. B. Smith, A. H. Stone and W. T. Tutte, The dissection of rectangles into squares, Duke Math. J., 7 (1940), 312-340.
%H A393664 Stuart Anderson, <a href="https://www.squaring.net/sq/ss/cpss/2-con-table.html">Table of 2-connected planar graphs</a>.
%H A393664 Stuart Anderson, <a href="https://www.squaring.net/downloads/downloads.html">Collections of squared rectangles, squared squares, and software for generating, processing and displaying them</a>.
%H A393664 Jim Williams, <a href="https://www.squaring.net/downloads/downloads.html#williams">Squared square solvers and graph generation code</a>.
%e A393664 It is a known result that the lowest possible order for a Compound Perfect Squared Square is 24 with the single solution having a side of 175 (discovered by T. H. Willcocks in 1948).
%Y A393664 Cf. A393600, A393598, A393599, A393600.
